# Memory Bank
At the start of EVERY task, read all files in memory-bank/ before doing anything else.
After significant work (new feature, bug fix, architectural change), update the relevant memory-bank/ files.
Use /newtask when context gets large to preserve state cleanly.

# Domain Rules — Clinical / Mental Health Data
- This app handles patient PII, diagnoses, medications, psychological assessments, and session transcripts
- Never log, print, or expose patient data in plaintext outside the Flask app context
- Never hardcode patient data or realistic-looking PII in source files or tests — use clearly fake placeholders (e.g. "Test Patient", DOB 2000-01-01)
- The `suicidal` keyword group in `sentiment_analysis.py` is a clinical safety signal — do not modify it without explicit user approval
- Do not add analytics, telemetry, external HTTP calls, or third-party integrations that could leak patient data
- Treat all `db.Text` fields on Patient and Session models as potentially sensitive

# Code Rules
- Entry point is `app_simple.py` — all Flask routes live there, do not split routes across files unless explicitly asked
- Follow existing route naming: list → `def patients()`, add → `def add_patient()`, detail → `def patient_detail(patient_id)`, edit → `def edit_patient(patient_id)`
- Always use `patient_id=x` / `appointment_id=x` in `url_for()` — never bare `id=x`
- Use SQLAlchemy 2.x API: `db.session.get(Model, id)` — not `Model.query.get(id)`
- Strip whitespace and coerce empty strings to `None` before saving form data
- When adding model columns: delete `instance/session_tracking.db` before restarting so schema is recreated
- Type hints required in analysis modules (`sentiment_analysis.py`, `patient_data_model.py`, etc.); optional in Flask routes
- PEP 8 throughout; section dividers `# ── Section ──` in `app_simple.py`
- New templates must extend `base.html` with `{% block title %}` and `{% block content %}`

# Behavior Rules
- Always ask before running terminal commands
- State your approach in one sentence before writing code
- If the request is ambiguous, ask one clarifying question before proceeding
- Never remove existing functionality unless explicitly told to
- After completing a task, summarise: what changed, what files were modified, and any follow-up items
